<TITLE> Magnificent Mahmudullah rescues Bangladesh </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 17 (bdnews24.com)  Mahmudullah celebrated a maiden century to help Bangladesh avoid the follow-on against New Zealand on the third day of the one-off Test at Seddon Park in Hamilton on Wednesday. The right-hander, who missed out on scoring a hundred against India, made 115 and featured in a record 145-run seventh wicket partnership with his skipper Shakib Al Hasan (87) after the side slumped to 196-6. Eventually, the Tigers were dismissed for 408, still 145 runs adrift of New Zealand's first innings score. The Black Caps were left to negotiate the last five overs of the day's play. Although they lost BJ Watling, who was brilliantly run out by the Bangladesh skipper for one, they ended on 9-1. Earlier, Bangladesh crumbled on the third morning losing five wickets before going to lunch on 211-6. Resuming on 87-1, the top order once again capitulated under the pressure after most of the batsmen got starts. Tamim Iqbal, who batted with plenty of aggression the previous evening, was tied down by the Kiwi seamers. He was eventually out to a false shot for 68. Junaid Siddique fell to Chris Martin for 21. Mohammed Ashraful didn't stick around long, and Aftab Ahmed's return to Test cricket after a two-year hiatus was cut short by a Daryl Tuffey outswi
